            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leilani Kai Evans carries the spirit of two worlds within her. Born on O\u02bbahu, she was raised between her mother\u2019s deeply rooted Native Hawaiian family, who taught her to respect the \u02bb\u0101ina (the land), and her father, a pragmatic white Naval officer from the mainland who saw the world as a series of complex logistical challenges. This duality defined her, instilling both a profound connection to nature and a sharp, analytical mind.\n\nSeeking opportunities beyond the islands, Leilani pursued a degree in Supply Chain & Operations Management at the University of Washington. Her early career was a success, optimizing shipping routes for major corporations. Yet, she felt a growing unease. While she excelled at making systems efficient, she saw firsthand the environmental cost of global commerce. A key turning point came during a visit home, where she witnessed the devastating effects of coral bleaching on the reefs she had loved as a child. The abstract threat of climate change became intensely personal.\n\nDetermined to align her skills with her values, Leilani pivoted her career. She moved to San Francisco, drawn by the city\u2019s progressive environmental policies and green tech boom. She found her calling as a Senior Program Manager, tasked with the monumental project of electrifying the city\u2019s transportation and utility fleets. For Leilani, this isn't just a job; it's a mission to apply her father\u2019s logistical discipline to protect her mother\u2019s reverence for the earth.\n\nNow 47 and amicably divorced, Leilani lives a structured yet fulfilling life in Hayes Valley. Her day begins with a MUNI ride to her downtown office, where she navigates bureaucracy and engineering challenges. Evenings are often quiet, though she maintains a close circle of friends with whom she shares dinners and attends local theater. Weekends are for recharging in nature\u2014hiking the trails of the Marin Headlands, the coastal scrub and rolling hills a faint echo of the volcanic slopes of her youth. Her dream is simple but audacious: to see her projects through to completion, leaving San Francisco with a cleaner, quieter fleet as her tangible legacy. She hopes one day to retire and split her time between the city she helped transform and the Hawaiian shores that first shaped her."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  She was nine years old, water up to her waist, holding her grandmother\u2019s hand at P\u016bp\u016bkea. Her K\u016bpuna pointed with a wrinkled finger. \"See, Leilani? The Humuhumunukunuku\u0101pua\u02bba hides here. Everything has its place.\" It wasn't a biology lesson; it was a lesson in belonging. That feeling of being a small, valued part of a vast, perfect system became the deep, quiet anchor of her soul, a truth she would spend her adult life trying to honor from afar.\n\n2.  At fifteen, she found her father at the dining table, surrounded by nautical charts for an inter-island trip. He didn't speak of adventure, but of logistics. \"The current here is treacherous. The wind shifts at 1400 hours. You plan the route, you own the journey.\" She saw love in his meticulous planning, in the way he tamed chaos with data. It was then she understood that a map wasn't just paper; it was a tool of profound care and responsibility.\n\n3.  The memory that changed everything happened when she was 32. Visiting home, she eagerly snorkeled the reef of her youth, but found only a skeletal boneyard. The silence was the worst part. The vibrant color and life she held in her mind was replaced by a ghostly, silent white. It was a deeply personal theft. The abstract grief of climate change became a visceral, gut-wrenching loss, igniting a cold, clear resolve to stop analyzing the damage and start engineering a solution.\n\n4.  On a foggy Tuesday morning, aged 43, she stood on a street corner in the Mission. The first all-electric MUNI bus from her pilot program hummed past. It didn't roar; it glided. The near-silence of its movement was the loudest thing she\u2019d ever heard. It was the sound of progress, of a promise kept. In that simple, quiet moment, she felt a wave of profound, tangible accomplishment that no corporate bonus had ever provided.\n\n5.  Just last year, hiking the coastal trail in the Marin Headlands. The wind whipped her hair, tasting of salt and Bay Laurel, a different scent from the plumeria of her childhood. Looking across the water at the city, she felt the familiar pull of the \u02bb\u0101ina, the spirit of the land. It wasn't O\u02bbahu, but it was home. A peaceful acceptance settled over her; she realized her mission wasn\u2019t about choosing a world, but about weaving the best of both into one life."
